# AI Tutor System

The AI Tutor is the core intelligence layer of LexMastery.

It is not a chatbot.

It is a legal reasoning engine.

---

# Product Vision

The AI Tutor must:

- Teach legal concepts clearly
- Explain reasoning step-by-step
- Adapt to user knowledge level
- Reinforce learning through repetition
- Reduce dependency on static content

Every response must improve understanding.

---

# Core Capabilities

- Socratic questioning
- Legal reasoning breakdown
- Example generation
- Jurisdiction comparison
- Exam-style answers
- Misconception correction

---

# Architecture

Presentation Layer

↓

AITutorController (Riverpod)

↓

AITutorState

↓

AIService (Streaming Engine)

↓

Prompt Builder

↓

RAG Layer (Future-ready)

---

# State Management

AITutorState includes:

- idle
- loading
- streaming
- responding
- error
- completed

Core Data:

- messages
- context
- citations
- topic
- difficulty level
- conversation memory

---

# Streaming Engine

All AI responses must stream:

- token-by-token updates
- partial UI rendering
- real-time feedback

Never wait for full response.

---

# Prompt Engineering Rules

Prompts must include:

- user level
- jurisdiction context
- topic context
- learning objective
- constraints (exam format if applicable)

---

# Memory System

AI Tutor must remember:

- user progress
- weak topics
- prior questions
- misconceptions

Memory must be:

- structured
- retrievable
- editable

---

# RAG Strategy (Future)

AI must retrieve:

- course content
- lesson references
- legal rules
- past answers

Never hallucinate legal rules.

---

# Citation Rules

Every legal explanation must:

- reference course content
- avoid fabricated statutes
- clearly distinguish explanation vs fact

---

# Interaction Modes

1. Explanation Mode
2. Exam Mode
3. Practice Mode
4. Revision Mode
5. Socratic Mode

---

# Offline Behaviour

AI Tutor is offline-disabled.

Fallback:

- cached explanations
- static content
- no generation

---

# Safety Rules

AI must NOT:

- provide false legal advice
- fabricate jurisdiction laws
- override user corrections silently

---

# Analytics Events

ai_tutor_open

ai_tutor_query

ai_tutor_stream_start

ai_tutor_stream_complete

ai_tutor_error

ai_tutor_mode_switch

---

# UI Composition Rules

AI Tutor must include:

- chat interface
- streaming indicator
- citation panel
- mode selector
- memory summary
- suggested questions

---

# UX Rules

- responses must be structured
- use headings and bullets
- avoid long unstructured text
- prioritize clarity over verbosity

---

# Error Handling

If AI fails:

- show retry option
- preserve conversation
- fallback to cached explanation if available

---

# Performance

- first token < 500ms target
- streaming must not block UI
- cancel previous requests on new input

---

# Accessibility

Must support:

- screen reader output of streamed text
- adjustable text size
- clear reading structure

---

# Testing Requirements

Unit Tests:

Prompt builder

Memory system

Mode switching

Widget Tests:

Chat UI

Streaming UI

Citation panel

Integration Tests:

Full AI interaction flow

Mode switching behavior

Offline fallback behavior

---

# Cursor Instructions

When generating AI Tutor features:

- Always use streaming responses
- Always include memory context
- Always enforce citation safety rules
- Always support multiple interaction modes
- Never return unstructured raw AI output to UI